{"id":"2206.05727","submitter":"Mahmoud Abdelkhalek","authors":"Mahmoud Abdelkhalek, Dror Baron, and Chau-Wai Wong","title":"Mismatched Estimation in the Distance Geometry Problem","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We investigate mismatched estimation in the context of the distance geometry\nproblem (DGP). In the DGP, for a set of points, we are given noisy measurements\nof pairwise distances between the points, and our objective is to determine the\ngeometric locations of the points. A common approach to deal with noisy\nmeasurements of pairwise distances is to compute least-squares estimates of the\nlocations of the points. However, these least-squares estimates are likely to\nbe suboptimal, because they do not necessarily maximize the correct likelihood\nfunction. In this paper, we argue that more accurate estimates can be obtained\nwhen an estimation procedure using the correct likelihood function of noisy\nmeasurements is performed. Our numerical results demonstrate that least-squares\nestimates can be suboptimal by several dB.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Jun 2022 12:46:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-14"}
